# Dependency install policy (Cloude)

**Default:** `npm ci` - installs exactly what package-lock.json specifies.

**Do not use npm install for:**
- CI / GitHub Actions
- Vercel / production build (installCommand)
- Docker image builds
- Routine local setup after clone or pull

**Use npm install only when intentionally changing dependencies:**
- `npm install <package>` to add or bump
- Then commit package.json and package-lock.json

## pnpm workspaces (e.g. SPRAY)

- Default: `pnpm install --frozen-lockfile`
- Vercel/npm sub-apps: `npm ci` when package-lock.json is the lock source

## Why

`npm install` may resolve new versions or unexpected packages. `npm ci` fails if lockfile is out of sync.

## Single lockfile per package manager (P2)

**pnpm workspace (SPRAY):**

- Source of truth: `pnpm-lock.yaml` at repo root only
- Do **not** add `package-lock.json` under `apps/*` or other workspace packages
- CI fails if `apps/web/package-lock.json` exists

**npm projects:**

- One `package-lock.json` per deploy unit (monorepo sub-app = own lock in that directory)
- Dependabot must update the lock in the **same directory** as the bumped `package.json`

## Dependabot major updates

- **Do not auto-merge** semver-major Dependabot PRs
- `dependabot.yml` uses `ignore: update-types: [version-update:semver-major]` for framework deps
- Major bumps (Next, React, TypeScript, etc.) require explicit owner review + build/audit
